I"‘<p>If one <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/continuous-state-dynamical-systems-share-a-common-structure">dynamical system</a> can be tweaked so that the resulting <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/attractors-and-repellors-have-opposite-behaviors-in-dynamical-systems">behavior</a> resembles the original one after a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/linear-transformations-are-perfectly-described-by-matrices">simple transformation</a>, then the two are structurally stable, forming a stable basin in the space of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dynamical-systems-have-a-certain-anatomy">dynamical systems</a>.</p>
